<!-- SECTION 2: OVERVIEW / INTRO + TL;DR -->
<section class="content-section" id="overview-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Ecommerce Business Registration in Delhi - Overview</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-bottom:20px;">
                    <p><strong>&#128204; TL;DR - Ecommerce Business Services at a Glance</strong></p>
                    <p>E-commerce business registration in India is a stack - Pvt Ltd or LLP entity setup, GST registration (mandatory under Section 24 of CGST Act for marketplace operators, with relaxed thresholds for sellers under Notification 34/2023), Trademark, IEC for cross-border, FSSAI for food, and Consumer Protection (E-Commerce) Rules 2020 compliance. TCS at 0.50 percent under Section 52 effective 10 July 2024. Patron runs the full stack at INR 9,999.</p>
                </div>
                <p><div class='table-responsive-wrapper'>
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Quick Reference</th><th>Details</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Governing Laws</td><td>Companies Act 2013 (entity) + CGST Act 2017 Section 24(ix), 24(x), 52, 9(5) + Consumer Protection Act 2019 with E-Commerce Rules 2020 + IT Act 2000 with Rules 2021 + DPDP Act 2023 + FDI Press Note 2 of 2018 + FSS Act 2006 + Foreign Trade Act 1992</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Applicable To</td><td>Three models - (1) E-Commerce Operators (Amazon, Flipkart, Meesho, Myntra style); (2) Sellers on marketplaces; (3) D2C-only brands selling exclusively through own website with payment gateway</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Timeline</td><td>End-to-end 15 to 25 working days for D2C / Marketplace Seller; 30 to 45 days for Marketplace Operator</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Cost (Patron)</td><td>INR 9,999 FIXED (Exl GST and Govt. Charges) for core bundle</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>TCS Rate (2026)</td><td>0.50% under Section 52 effective 10 July 2024 (reduced from 1%)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Goods Seller Threshold (through ECO)</td><td>INR 40 lakh per Notification 34/2023 (INR 20 lakh special states)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Penalty (no GST)</td><td>Section 122 CGST - 100% of tax due OR INR 10,000 (whichever higher)</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div></p>
                <p>E-commerce in India is not a single registration - it is a regulatory stack spanning entity setup, GST (with specific provisions for marketplace operators and sellers), brand protection, sector-specific licences, foreign trade authorisation (for cross-border) and consumer protection compliance. The 2024-2026 regulatory environment has materially changed - TCS under Section 52 reduced from 1% to 0.50% effective 10 July 2024 (improving seller cash flow), Notification 34/2023 raised the GST registration threshold for goods sellers through ECOs from 'mandatory regardless of turnover' to INR 40 lakh (INR 20 lakh for special category states), and the Consumer Protection (E-Commerce) Rules 2020 (effective 23 July 2020) tightened obligations on grievance officers, product listings, return policies and fake reviews. The right approach is to choose the business model first - D2C brand on own website, marketplace seller across Amazon / Flipkart / Meesho / Myntra, marketplace operator running the platform itself or services aggregator under Section 9(5) - because each carries different GST consequences. Patron Accounting's Delhi office runs the full stack at INR 9,999 (Exl GST and Govt. Charges).</p>
                <p>Content is reviewed quarterly for accuracy.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 3: WHAT IS GSTAT APPEAL FILING -->
<section class="content-section" id="what-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="two-column">
            <div class="column-content">
                <h2 class="section-title">What E-Commerce Business Registration Actually Covers</h2>
                <div class="content-text what-is-definition">
                    
                    <p>E-commerce business registration in India is a multi-layer setup that depends on the chosen business model. The three primary models are: (a) <strong>E-Commerce Operator (ECO)</strong> running a marketplace platform that hosts third-party sellers and collects payments (Amazon, Flipkart, Meesho, Myntra, Swiggy, Zomato, Uber); (b) <strong>Seller on third-party marketplaces</strong> (D2C brands and MSMEs listing on existing platforms); and (c) <strong>D2C-only brand</strong> selling through its own website with direct payment gateway integration.</p>

<p>The GST consequences differ materially across these three models. ECOs face mandatory GST registration under Section 24(x) regardless of turnover, must collect TCS at 0.50% under Section 52 from every supplier payment (effective from 10 July 2024 per Notification 15/2024-Central Tax, reduced from the earlier 1% rate) and file Form GSTR-8 monthly. Sellers on marketplaces face registration under Section 24(ix), with thresholds relaxed by Notification 34/2023 to INR 40 lakh for goods (INR 20 lakh for special category states) and Notification 65/2017 to INR 20 lakh for services. D2C-only brands face only the standard turnover threshold (INR 20 lakh services / INR 40 lakh goods), but inter-state supply triggers mandatory registration even below the threshold.</p>

<p>Beyond GST, the e-commerce stack requires entity setup (Pvt Ltd via SPICe+ or LLP via FiLLiP); Trademark filing for brand protection (with 50% fee rebate for DPIIT-recognised startups); IEC for cross-border shipments under the Foreign Trade (D&R) Act 1992; FSSAI license for food e-commerce under the FSS Act 2006; Udyam or MSME registration; Delhi Shop and Establishment license; and ongoing compliance under the Consumer Protection (E-Commerce) Rules 2020 (grievance officer, nodal officer for law enforcement, mandatory product listing details, no fake reviews, transparent return / refund policy), the IT (Intermediary Guidelines and Digital Media Ethics Code) Rules 2021 (for marketplace operators), the DPDP Act 2023 (privacy notice, consent, breach notification - phased implementation through 2026) and the FDI policy under Press Note 2 of 2018 by DPIIT (marketplace model only; inventory model not permitted for FDI-backed e-commerce). Patron Accounting's Delhi office bundles the essential registrations at INR 9,999 with add-ons for sector-specific licences and ongoing compliance.</p>

                </div>
                <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top:20px;">
                    <p><strong>Key Terms for Ecommerce Business:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>E-Commerce Operator (ECO):</strong> Per Section 2(45) CGST Act - any person who owns, operates or manages a digital platform for electronic commerce; mandatorily registered under Section 24(x) regardless of turnover.</p>
<p><strong>Section 24(x) CGST Act:</strong> Mandatory GST registration for every ECO; required in each State or UT of operations.</p>
<p><strong>Section 24(ix) CGST Act:</strong> Mandatory GST registration for persons supplying through an ECO collecting TCS; subject to Notification 34/2023 (goods INR 40 lakh) and Notification 65/2017 (services INR 20 lakh) relaxations.</p>
<p><strong>Section 52 CGST Act (TCS):</strong> TCS at 0.50% (0.25% CGST + 0.25% SGST or UTGST, or 0.50% IGST); effective from 10 July 2024 (reduced from 1%); reported in Form GSTR-8.</p>
<p><strong>Section 9(5) CGST Act:</strong> Notified services where the ECO is deemed supplier - cab aggregators, accommodation booking, housekeeping, restaurant services through food delivery platforms.</p>
<p><strong>Form GST REG-07:</strong> ECO TCS registration form under Rule 12 CGST Rules; Rule 12(1A) for multi-state declarations.</p>
<p><strong>Form GSTR-8:</strong> Monthly TCS return by ECO; due 10th of next month.</p>
<p><strong>Notification 34/2023-Central Tax:</strong> Dated 31 July 2023 - relaxation for goods suppliers through ECO; registration required only above INR 40 lakh.</p>
<p><strong>Consumer Protection (E-Commerce) Rules 2020:</strong> Notified 23 July 2020; mandate grievance officer, nodal officer, transparent listings.</p>
<p><strong>FDI Press Note 2 of 2018:</strong> Marketplace model only; inventory model not permitted for FDI-backed e-commerce.</p>

                </div>
            </div>
