<!-- SECTION 8: DOCUMENTS REQUIRED -->
<section class="content-section" id="documents-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Documents Checklist for Ecommerce Registration</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                <ul>
                    <li>PAN and Aadhaar of all directors / partners / shareholders</li>
                    <li>Passport-size photographs of all directors / partners</li>
                    <li>Residential address proof of directors / partners (electricity bill or bank statement under 2 months)</li>
                    <li>Email IDs and Indian mobile numbers for OTP-based MCA verification</li>
                    <li>Three proposed business names (in case the first is taken)</li>
                    <li>Delhi registered office proof - rent agreement, NOC from owner, latest utility bill</li>
                    <li>Detailed product / service description and category list with HSN codes</li>
                    <li>Brand assets - logo, trade name, original artwork (for trademark filing)</li>
                    <li>Domain ownership proof (if website already exists)</li>
                    <li>Bank account details for the entity (for GST and IEC bank verification)</li>
                    <li>Photo of business premises with directors / partners (for GST registration)</li>
                    <li>FSSAI: kitchen / warehouse layout, food safety management plan, water test report (if food)</li>
                    <li>IEC: bank certificate, cancelled cheque (if cross-border)</li>
                    <li>For Marketplace Operators: flow diagram of supplier onboarding and payment settlement; intended platform model documentation</li>
                    <li>For FDI-backed entities: investor declaration on Press Note 2 marketplace model compliance</li>
                    <li>For Sellers selling through marketplaces: intended marketplaces list, expected monthly GMV by marketplace</li>
                </ul>

            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 9: CHALLENGES -->
<section class="content-section" id="challenges-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Common Challenges and Patron Solutions</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="table-responsive-wrapper">
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Challenge</th><th>Impact</th><th>How Patron Accounting Solves It</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Founders confusing ECO and Seller GST treatment</td><td>Many believe they need to register under Section 24(x) (mandatory) when actually they qualify under Section 24(ix) with Notification 34/2023 relaxation - registration only above INR 40 lakh for goods.</td><td>Patron classifies the business correctly at engagement start - ECO (own and operate the platform), Seller (third-party supplier on someone else's platform) or D2C (own website + payment gateway). The classification drives GST treatment, threshold applicability, TCS implications, and Form REG-01 vs REG-07 choice.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>TCS cash flow drag for marketplace sellers</td><td>The 0.50% TCS (reduced from 1% on 10 July 2024) on every marketplace payout ties up working capital until GST refund or credit utilisation.</td><td>Patron projects the TCS cash drag at engagement and recommends the seller mix - heavy D2C component for cash flow plus marketplaces for reach. Monthly GSTR reconciliation set up to claim TCS credit in the same month it accrues (no carry-forward delay).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Consumer Protection (E-Commerce) Rules 2020 grievance and nodal officer appointments not done</td><td>This is the SINGLE most common consumer complaint enforcement trigger; District Consumer Disputes Redressal Commissions actively cite Rules 2020 violations.</td><td>Patron appoints the Grievance Officer (consumer grievances) and Nodal Officer (law enforcement coordination) at registration time, with full contact details published on the platform. 48-hour acknowledgement and 30-day redressal SLA calendared. The 9-point compliance pack including no fake reviews, transparent listings and accurate inventory disclosure is set up from day one.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>FDI restrictions for inventory-holding e-commerce</td><td>Press Note 2 of 2018 prohibits FDI-backed e-commerce from owning inventory; many D2C brands starting with foreign funding face this restriction without realising it.</td><td>Patron structures the entity to comply with Press Note 2 marketplace model restrictions - separating inventory ownership from the e-commerce platform via a related entity, using consignment arrangements or restricting FDI to the parent holding company while operations sit in an Indian-funded subsidiary. Restructuring after a funding round is materially more expensive.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>DPDP Act 2023 implementation</td><td>Phased rollout through 2026 with significant operational implications for e-commerce platforms handling personal data; privacy notice, consent management, breach notification and data principal rights handling all need to be operationalised.</td><td>Patron sets up the DPDP-compliant privacy notice and consent management at registration; identifies the Data Fiduciary obligations specific to the business model; maps the high-risk processing activities; documents the breach notification protocol; for significant Data Fiduciaries, additional DPO appointment and DPIA obligations are planned.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Inter-state supply triggering mandatory GST for D2C below threshold</td><td>The first sale shipped to another state without GSTIN exposes the founder to Section 122 penalty (100% of tax or INR 10,000, whichever higher) even at low turnover.</td><td>Patron sequences GST registration before the first inter-state shipment for D2C brands shipping nationally - GSTIN obtained in 5-7 working days, preventing the structural compliance gap that catches first-time founders.</td></tr>

                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

