                <aside class="faq-expanded__aside">
                    <h2 class="faq-expanded__title">FAQs: Ecommerce Business Registration in Delhi</h2>
                    <p class="faq-expanded__lead">Common questions about Ecommerce Business Registration for Delhi businesses, answered by our CA and CS team.</p>
                    @include('partials.faq-enquiry-form', ['enquiryLocation' => 'Delhi', 'enquiryService' => 'Ecommerce Business Registration in Delhi'])
                </aside>
                <div class="faq-expanded__list">
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-1">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What registrations are required to start an e-commerce business in India?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>A stack - (a) entity (Pvt Ltd via SPICe+ or LLP via FiLLiP), (b) GST under Section 24 CGST Act (mandatory for ECOs under Section 24(x), threshold-based for sellers under Section 24(ix) with Notification 34/2023 relaxation), (c) Trademark for brand protection, (d) IEC for cross-border, (e) FSSAI for food, (f) Udyam or MSME, (g) Delhi Shop and Establishment, (h) Consumer Protection Rules 2020 compliance documentation, (i) IT Rules 2021 for marketplace operators and (j) DPDP Act 2023 privacy compliance.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-2">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Is GST registration mandatory for selling on Amazon and Flipkart?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>For goods - registration required only if aggregate turnover exceeds INR 40 lakh per Notification 34/2023-Central Tax dated 31 July 2023 (INR 20 lakh for special category states). For services - exempt under INR 20 lakh per Notification 65/2017-Central Tax. The earlier 'mandatory regardless of turnover' rule has been relaxed; however, the marketplace platforms typically require GSTIN before onboarding sellers as a commercial precaution.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-3">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the GST TCS rate for e-commerce in 2026?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>TCS under Section 52 CGST Act 2017 is at 0.50 percent (0.25 percent CGST plus 0.25 percent SGST or UTGST, or 0.50 percent IGST) on the net value of taxable supplies; effective from 10 July 2024 per Notification 15/2024-Central Tax (reduced from the earlier 1 percent rate). ECOs deduct this from supplier payouts and remit it in Form GSTR-8 by the 10th of the next month.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-4">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Do D2C brands selling only through their own website need GST registration?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Standard turnover threshold applies - INR 40 lakh for goods and INR 20 lakh for services (INR 20 lakh and INR 10 lakh respectively for special category states). Critical exception - any inter-state supply (shipping to a customer in another state) triggers mandatory GST registration even below the threshold, regardless of turnover. Most D2C brands shipping nationally cross this trigger from day one.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-5">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the Consumer Protection (E-Commerce) Rules 2020 compliance for online sellers?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Under Consumer Protection Act 2019 read with Rules dated 23 July 2020 - appoint Grievance Officer (consumer grievances; acknowledgement within 48 hours; redressal within 30 days) and Nodal Officer (law enforcement coordination); publish complete product listings (seller name, address, return policy, warranty, country of origin, expiry); no fake reviews or manipulated ratings; transparent cancellation, return, refund policy; no manipulation of search results.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-6">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Should I register e-commerce as Private Limited Company or LLP?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Private Limited is preferred for - FDI fundraising (institutional investors require Pvt Ltd), ESOP plans for employees, eventual IPO. LLP is preferred for - lighter compliance, no FDI plans, founder-controlled growth. Most growth-stage e-commerce founders choose Pvt Ltd for the equity fundraising optionality. The Private Limited governance burden is heavier (statutory audit mandatory, 4 board meetings per year, AOC-4 plus MGT-7) but justified by the fundraising flexibility.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-7">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How long does e-commerce business registration take in 2026?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>End-to-end 15 to 25 working days for D2C brand or Marketplace Seller. Entity (Pvt Ltd or LLP) 7-10 days; GST 5-7 days; Trademark filing receipt 3-5 days; IEC 5-10 days; FSSAI 30-60 days for food (parallel track); Udyam same day; Consumer Protection Rules 2020 documentation 5-7 days; marketplace seller onboarding 7-15 days. Marketplace Operator setup with multi-state Section 24(x) registration is 30 to 45 days.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-8">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is Section 9(5) and which businesses does it cover?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Section 9(5) CGST Act read with Notification 17/2017-CT(R) is the deemed-supplier provision - for notified services, the ECO is treated as the supplier and pays GST directly while the underlying restaurant, driver or hotel partner does not pay GST on the platform-routed transaction. Notified services include cab aggregators (Uber, Ola), accommodation booking (MakeMyTrip, Oyo), housekeeping and restaurant services through food delivery platforms (Swiggy, Zomato). ECOs in this space file standard returns plus Form GSTR-8 for non-Section-9(5) transactions.</p></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Quick Answers -->
            <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top:32px;">
                <p><strong>Quick Answers</strong></p>
                <p><strong>Q: Entity options?</strong> A: Pvt Ltd (SPICe+ on MCA21 v3) or LLP (FiLLiP on MCA21 v3).</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Core GST statute?</strong> A: CGST Act 2017 - Section 24(x) ECO mandatory; Section 24(ix) supplier through ECO; Section 52 TCS; Section 9(5) deemed supplier.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: TCS rate (2026)?</strong> A: 0.50% effective from 10 July 2024 - reduced from earlier 1%.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Goods seller threshold (through ECO)?</strong> A: INR 40 lakh per Notification 34/2023 (INR 20 lakh special states).</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Service seller threshold (through ECO)?</strong> A: INR 20 lakh per Notification 65/2017 (INR 10 lakh special states).</p>
                <p><strong>Q: ECO registration form?</strong> A: Form GST REG-07 (with Rule 12(1A) multi-state declarations).</p>
                <p><strong>Q: ECO monthly TCS return?</strong> A: Form GSTR-8 by 10th of next month.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Consumer Protection statute?</strong> A: Consumer Protection Act 2019 read with E-Commerce Rules 2020 dated 23 July 2020.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: IT compliance?</strong> A: IT Act 2000 read with IT (Intermediary Guidelines) Rules 2021.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: FDI policy?</strong> A: Press Note 2 of 2018 by DPIIT - marketplace model only; inventory model not permitted for FDI.</p>
