                <p>Three immediate timing concerns govern e-commerce registration. First, <strong>inter-state supply triggers mandatory GST registration regardless of turnover</strong> for D2C brands - the first sale shipped to another state without GSTIN exposes the founder to Section 122 penalty (100% of tax or INR 10,000, whichever higher). Second, <strong>marketplace seller onboarding</strong> (Amazon, Flipkart, Meesho, Myntra) is gated on GSTIN even though the threshold relaxation under Notification 34/2023 may not strictly require it - get the GSTIN first to avoid platform-side rejection.</p>
                <p>Third, the <strong>TCS at 0.50% (effective 10 July 2024)</strong> ties up working capital at every marketplace payout cycle; planning the GSTR reconciliation calendar at registration prevents permanent cash flow drag. Post-registration, the recurring deadlines are stringent - GSTR-1 by 11th of next month, GSTR-3B by 20th, GSTR-8 (ECO TCS) by 10th, TDS by 7th, ROC filings on annual due dates, FSSAI annual renewal, Trademark renewal 10-year cycles. Patron Accounting's CA and CS team in Delhi runs the full stack from one engagement.</p>
